<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO ANONYMOUS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Dec 17 13:52:49 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
REPLY TO ANONYMOUS,<br><br>
Thank you for your kind words. May I share a few words with you regarding the course. The seminar will be ten weeks: one evening per week for 3 hours. The first two weeks will introduce the students to the peoples and culture of Viet Nam, the realities and mythology of Vietnamese-American War, and sources. Weeks 3-7 will be presentations that reflect the a diversity of &quot;Vietnam-Era&quot; experiences: students will hear from combat veterans, physicians and nurses who treated the wounded, men-women who were in Viet Nam but not in combat, POW and MIA perspectives, ARVN perspectives, Vietnamese-American perspectives, and post-war issues important to veterans especially health-related issues. <br><br>
Also represented will be the views and experiences of men and women who have recently traveled to Viet Nam in a variety of capacities, i.e. businessmen, teachers, physicians, and nutritionists.  <br><br>
On the 8th week of class my students and I will assemble at the California Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Sacramento for an evening evening to commemorate life, and to remember....<br><br>
I am working with colleagues at the Vietnam Veterans of California in Santa Rosa, with the Bach Viet Foundation in Sacramento, and with other organizations in the hope that the evening at the Memorial will be widely announced. <br><br>
Anonymous..... please write again; let me and my students better understand you points of view. Further, please tell others about this &quot;dialog string&quot; and ask others to respond to the PBS website.<br><br>
Regards and best wishes.<br><br>

